{"title":"The case for templating","markdown":{"headingText":"The case for templating","containsRefs":false,"markdown":"```{r}\n#| label: business-case\n#| echo: false\n#| fig-cap: Quarto generated reports save time and minimise human error\nknitr::include_graphics(here::here(\"images\",\"business-case.png\"))\n```\n\n\n## Templated reporting\n\n### Benefits\n\nThere are a number of benefits to investing in templated or parameterised reporting:\n\n-   **Reduced repetition:** Avoiding repetition of producing basic or standard analysis.\n\n-   **Better publication workflow:**\n\n-   **Consistency:** Can provide greater confidence with results, with less chance of human error.\n\n-   **Capability transfer:** Analysis in a structured or templated format can be useful for knowledge transfer.\n\n### Headaches\n\nTemplated reporting is not without all faults.\n\nTransforming ad-hoc processes to more structured end to end reports can be quite an investment, particularly if users aren't already using the processes. It is advisableot consider building a Quarto template of a report to be a capital investment. You spend the additional effort to build up the capability to develop reports quicker, more consistently and even automatically.\n\n```{r}\n#| label: report-process\n#| echo: false\n#| fig-cap: An example of how transformational structured reports can be\nknitr::include_graphics(here::here(\"images\",\"report-process.png\"))\n```\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"engine":"knitr"},"render":{